Nagarajan Murugesan v Grand Rich Electrical & Engineering Pte. Ltd. and others
[2023] SGDC 64

Case Number:District Court Suit No S 1040 of 2019, District Court Appeal No 4 of 2023
Decision Date:18 April 2023

Coram: Clement Seah Chi-Ling
Counsel Name(s): Michael Han Hean Juan and Jamie Neo Jie Min (Hoh Law Corporation) for the Plaintiff; Charles Phua Cheng Sye and Joshua Ho Jun Yang (PKWA Law Practice LLC) for the 1st and 2nd Defendants; Tang Jin Sheng, Joshua Lin Weizhi and Michelle Cheong Shi Yun (WhiteFern LLC) for the 3rd Defendant.

18 April 2023

District Judge Clement Seah Chi-Ling:

Introduction

1       The Plaintiff was at all material times an Indian national who was employed as a construction labourer by the 1st Defendant under a work permit.

2       The Plaintiff claimed against the 1st, 2nd and 3rd Defendants for damages arising out of an accident which occurred at Yishun Avenue 7 near Lamp Post 50 (the “Worksite”). The 1st Defendant was the Plaintiff’s employer. The 2nd Defendant was the main contractor and occupier of the Worksite. The 3rd Defendant was the employer of a banksman working at a construction site located near the Worksite.

3       The Plaintiff’s case was that the accident was caused by the negligence of 1st, 2nd and 3rd Defendant, and that of negligence of their employees for which the 1st, 2nd and 3rd Defendant were vicariously liable.

Undisputed Facts

4       On 16 May 2019 ("the material day"), the Plaintiff was instructed to assist in excavation works at the Worksite in the role of a banksman. The Plaintiff and the operator of the excavator would carry out excavation works at the Worksite.

5       The Plaintiff’s employer, the 1st Defendant, was engaged by the 2nd Defendant to supply an excavator together with a trained operator. The excavator was driven by an operator, Jayaraman Vanmigunathan (the “Operator"), who was employed by the 1st Defendant.

6       The Worksite was situated adjacent to the 3rd Defendant’s worksite which was located beside the 3rd lane of the 3-lane carriageway along Yishun Avenue 7 near lamp post 50 (the "3rd Defendant’s Worksite"). Barriers had been placed around the Worksite to separate the Worksite from the other parts of the public road. A picture showing the two worksites is reproduced below. In the picture “YJE Work Area” denotes the Worksite while “MH-7 Work Site” denotes the 3rd Defendant’s Worksite.

7       At the material time, a truck (the “3rd Defendant’s Truck") had arrived and intended to turn into the 3rd Defendant’s Worksite. However, there was insufficient space for the 3rd Defendant’s Truck to reverse into the 3rd Defendant’s Worksite. The Plaintiff was standing at the front right side of the excavator at all material times.

8       At this time, the excavator suddenly moved forward and collided into the Plaintiff. As a result of the collision, the Plaintiff suffered the following injuries:

(a)     Right foot open lisfranc fracture dislocation with severe degloving injury

(b)     Right ankle medial malleolus fracture

(c)     Left bimalleolar ankle fracture with multiple associated foot fractures.

The Parties’ Case

The Plaintiff's Case

9       The Plaintiff’s case was that the accident was caused by the breach of the statutory and common law duties of the 1st, 2nd and 3rd Defendant and that of the negligence of their employees, for which the 1st, 2nd and 3rd Defendant were vicariously liable.

10     The Plaintiff’s version was that, as the designated banksman for the Worksite on the material day, he had instructed the Operator to stop the excavator as he had observed that the 3rd Defendant’s Truck was attempting to enter the 3rdDefendant’s Worksite and would require more space to do so.

11     The Plaintiff averred that he had given the signal to the Operator to stop the excavator and therefore he did not expect the excavator to move. He had thereafter walked to the front right corner of the excavator to pull the water barriers inwards to create more space for the 3rd Defendant’s Truck to reverse.

12     However, the Operator suddenly moved the excavator forward when the 3rdDefendant's traffic controller, Neelamegam Alagu ("Neelamegam"), directed the Operator to do so. As a result, the excavator collided into the Plaintiff and caused him serious personal injuries.

13     The Plaintiff contended that the accident was caused by the negligence of the Operator in moving the excavator in the absence of directions from the Plaintiff as the designated banksman, as well as the 3rd Defendant’s banksman, Neelamegam, in directing the excavator to move forward without first ascertaining that it was safe to do so.

The 1st and 2nd Defendant’s Case

14     The lst and 2nd Defendant’s case was that prior to the accident, a dump truck had arrived at the Worksite and had parked behind the excavator. All of the lst Defendant's employees, including the Plaintiff, were required to leave the Worksite to help load materials onto the dump truck.

15     A commotion occurred when the 3rd Defendants’ Truck could not enter the 3rd Defendant’s Worksite because it was blocked by the water barriers surrounding the Worksite.

16     The Plaintiff, who had previously came out from the Worksite to help with the unloading of the material, then re-entered the Worksite on his own accord to pull the water barriers around the Worksite to make space for the 3rd Defendants’ Truck. The Plaintiff did not inform and/or alert the Operator that he had re-entered the Worksite. While pulling the water barriers, the Plaintiff stood in the excavator’s blind spot, in breach of the safety protocols.

17     The 3rd Defendants’ representative then shouted at the Operator to move the excavator forward to make space for the 3rd Defendants’ Truck to manoeuvre. The Operator did so without realising that the Plaintiff was standing in the excavator’s blind spot, as he was under the impression that all of the 1st and 2nd Defendants’ workers had exited the Worksite. When the Operator moved the excavator forward, the excavator ran over the Plaintiff’s foot.

18     The 1st Defendant did not deny that it should bear some liability for the Plaintiff’s injuries. However, the 1st and 2nd Defendant’s position was that the 2nd Defendant should not be liable to the Plaintiff at all as the manner in which the works were carried out were not within the 2nd Defendant’s control, and the Worksite was not an unsafe area.

19     The 1st and 2nd Defendant’s position was that the 3rd Defendant should also bear some liability for the accident as the 3rd Defendant’s banksman, Neelamegam, had directed the excavator to move forward. When doing so, the 3rd Defendant’s banksman should have alerted the Operator of the Plaintiff’s presence, but he failed to do so.

20     The 1st and 2nd Defendant’s also averred that the Plaintiff was the proximate cause of the accident and thus contributorily negligent as the Plaintiff had, inter alia, failed to follow safety protocols implemented at the worksite by standing in the blind spot of the excavator without warning the Operator of his presence. He further did so while the excavator’s engine was still on, and failed to move away when he knew or ought to have known that the excavator was going to move forward.

The 3rd Defendant’s Case

21     The 3rd Defendant denied all liability to the Plaintiff. The 3rd Defendant’s case was that it did not owe a duty of care to the Plaintiff as there was no proximity of relationship between the 3rd Defendant and the Plaintiff and/or his employer.

22     Even if the 3rd Defendant were found to owe a duty of care to the Plaintiff, the 3rd Defendant submitted that it had not breached the duty of care because the 3rd Defendant’s employee never gave any instructions to the Operator to move the excavator. Even if the 3rd Defendant’s employee did give instructions to the Operator (which was denied), there was no reason why the Operator should have listened to the instructions of the 3rd Defendant’s employee, given the clear protocol that Operator should only take instructions from the 1st Defendant’s banksman.

23     As such, the 3rd Defendant’s position was that the accident was caused solely by the negligence of the lst and/or 2nd Defendant and/or the Plaintiff.

24     In the event the 3rd Defendant were found liable, they submitted that the Plaintiff should be held contributorily negligent to the extent of 50% against the Defendants collectively primarily because the Plaintiff knowingly placed himself in a dangerous position where the Operator could not possibly see him.

The Liability Trial

25     The matter was fixed for a liability trial over two tranches with the first tranche on 25 July 2022 and the second tranche from 27 to 29 September 2022.

26     The following witnesses gave evidence at the liability trial:

(a)     The Plaintiff, Nagarajan Murugesan;

(b)     The 1st Defendant’s excavator operator, Jayaraman Vanmigunathan (the “Operator");

(c)     The 1st Defendant’s Director, Arockiadoss Prem Kumar Sadeesh Mathew ("Arockiadoss");

(d)     The 2nd Defendant’s site supervisor, Kasinathan Ramesh ("Kasinathan"); and

(e)     The 3rd Defendant’s site supervisor, Murugaiyan Velmurugan ("Murugaiyan").

Issues

27     Based on the pleadings and the parties’ closing submissions, the issues that arose for my consideration were as follows:

(a)     Whether the 1st Defendant was liable under the tort of negligence as the Plaintiff’s employer for the Plaintiff’s injuries?

(b)     Whether the Operator was negligent such that the 1st Defendant should be vicariously liable for his negligence?

(c)     Whether the 2nd Defendant was liable under the tort of negligence as the Main Contractor cum Occupier for the Plaintiff’s injuries?

(d)     If the Operator were negligent, whether the 2nd Defendant was also vicariously liable for the negligence of the Operator under the principles of dual vicarious liability?

(e)     Whether the 3rd Defendant’s banksman / traffic controller, Neelamegam, was negligent such that the 3rd Defendant was vicariously liable for his negligence?

(f)     Whether the Plaintiff was contributory negligent, and if so, the apportionment of liability among the parties.

My decision

28     At the end of the trial on liability, I found as follows:

(a)     That 1st Defendant was liable to the Plaintiff both under the tort of negligence and under the doctrine of vicarious liability.

(b)     That 2nd Defendant was not liable to the Plaintiff both under the tort of negligence and under the doctrine of dual vicarious liability.

(c)     That 3rd Defendant was liable to the Plaintiff under the doctrine of vicarious liability for Neelamegam’s negligence.

29     In terms of apportionment of liability, I found the Plaintiff contributorily negligent to the extent of 33.33%. As between the 1st Defendant and 3rd Defendant, I found the 1st Defendant liable to the extent of 56.67%, and 3rd Defendant to the liable to the extent of 10%. I therefore granted Plaintiff interlocutory judgment against 1st Defendant and 3rd Defendant for 66.67% of the damages to be assessed. As no contribution proceedings have been brought between the 1st and 3rd Defendants, I made no contribution orders as between the 1st and 3rd Defendants.

30     The Plaintiff is dissatisfied with the whole of my decision and has filed the present appeal. The 1st Defendant and 3rd Defendant did not file any cross-appeals.

31     I set out the detailed reasons for my decision below.

Liability of 1st Defendant as Plaintiff’s employer under the tort of negligence

32     The four-fold test for the common law tort of negligence is set out in Miah Rasel v 5 Ways Engineering Services Pte Ltd [2018] 3 SLR 480 (at [26]) (“Miah Rasel”) as follows: (a) the defendant had to have owed the claimant a duty of care; (b) the defendant’s conduct had to have breached the duty of care by falling below the requisite standard of care; (c) the claimant had to have suffered loss; and (d) the defendant’s breach of duty had to have been a cause of the claimant’s loss.

33     The framework for establishing a duty of care is as set out in Spandeck Engineering (S) Pte Ltd v Defence Science & Technology Agency [2007] 4 SLR(R) 100 (“Spandeck”). The test for determining the imposition of a duty of care is a two-stage test comprising of first, proximity and second, policy considerations, which were together preceded by the threshold question of factual foreseeability (Spandeck at [115]). If the threshold question of factual foreseeability were satisfied, then the first stage of the test required sufficient legal proximity between the claimant and the defendant, which is determined by the closeness of the parties’ relationship, including physical, circumstantial and causal proximity supported by the twin criteria of voluntary assumption of responsibility and actual reliance. If established, there would be a prima facie duty of care. The second stage then involves a consideration of policy considerations to decide if the prima facie duty should be negated, such as the presence of a contractual matrix within which parties have defined their rights and liabilities, or the relative bargaining positions of the parties (Spandeck at [83]).

34     In the case of an employer and employee relationship, there is usually no dispute that a duty of care exists. As the learned authors of The Law of Torts in Singapore (2nd ed, 2016, Academy Publishing) (“The Law of Torts in Singapore”) noted at [04.010]:

It is clear that a general duty is owed by an employer towards its employees to take reasonable care of the latter’s safety at work. With respect to employer’s duties to employees for personal injuries, it is noted that the employment relationship itself, as indicated in the Spandeck framework, gives rise to circumstantial proximity under the first stage for establishing a duty of care. Once an employment relationship is established, there is usually no dispute over the existing of duty of care for personal injuries suffered by the employee. It has been traditionally accepted that the employer’s duties include taking reasonable care to provide competent staff, adequate material, a roper system of work and effective supervision….

35     In relation to the 1st Defendant, the issues of causation and loss were not severely disputed. The key issue that arose for determination was whether the 1st Defendant had breached the duty of care owed to the Plaintiff. The two arguments advanced by the Plaintiff for contending that 1st Defendant had breached its duty of care were as follows:

(a)     The 1st Defendant failed to exercise effective supervision of the work being carried out by the Plaintiff and the Operator at the Worksite so as to ensure that such work was carried out safely; and

(b)     The 1st Defendant failed to take such measures as were necessary to ensure that adequate safety measures were taken in respect of any machinery, equipment, plant, article or process used by employees at the Worksite, in breach of Section 12(3)(b)(i) of the Workplace Health and Safety Act (Cap 354A, 2009 Rev Ed) (“WSHA”): see Plaintiff’s Closing Submissions (“PCS”) at [26].

Failure to exercise effective supervision

36     It has traditionally been accepted that an employer’s duties include having effective supervision over its employees: See The Law of Torts in Singapore at [04.010].

37     It was not disputed that at the time of the accident, the Plaintiff’s supervisor, Nathan Raja, was not at the Worksite. Nathan Raja was an employee of the 1st Defendant. He was not called as a witness at trial. The evidence at trial was that Nathan Raja had left the Worksite and gone to the back of the excavator together with other employees of the 1st Defendant to unload materials from a truck.

38     The Plaintiff’s case was that given that Nathan Raja had gone to the back of the excavator to assist with the unloading of materials, then it was likely that he would have seen the 3rd Defendant’s truck arriving at the third lane and attempting to reverse into the 3rd Defendant’s Worksite, and encountering difficulties while doing so. Nathan Raja, however, did not return to the Worksite to direct the movement of the excavator, give directions for the shifting of the water barriers, and/or give any instructions to facilitate the movement of the excavator. Given that the 2nd Defendant (the main contractor)’s site supervisor, Kasinathan, was similarly away, this effectively left the Operator and the Plaintiff in a lurch, with no guidance or supervision whatsoever. According to the Operator, he thus ended up following the instructions of the 3rd Defendant’s banksman when he moved the excavator forward:

Notes of Evidence (“ NE ”) 27 September 2022 p. 54 (Re-examination of DW1 by 1&2DC)

Q:    Okay. Now earlier on … solicitor for the 3rd defendant asked this question of you, whether you accept that points 4 and 7 as set out in page 55, is part of the safe procedure for the operation of the excavator. Your answer was “Yes, I want to explain”. So what is it that you want to explain?

A:    At that time, when I saw the workplace---the worksite, there was nobody around, and the lorry needed to go in so as not to cause any disturbance, it ended up being a situation where I have to follow what the [3rd Defendant’s] banksman said. If Nathan Raja was in front and had said not to go, not to move, I would have done so.

(emphasis added)

39     With Nathan Raja being absent to give directions, the Plaintiff attempted to move the water barriers inwards, while the Operator moved the excavator forward upon the instruction of 3rd Defendant’s banksman, seemingly without any coordination between the Operator and the Plaintiff. The accident then occurred.

40     Against this backdrop, I accepted the Plaintiff’s argument that when the 3rd Defendant’s Truck arrived, Nathan Raja ought to have been aware that his coordination of the areas of the Worksite where the excavator had stopped was crucial. In failing to coordinate, Nathan Raja had failed in his duty to effectively supervise the Plaintiff and the Operator, which in turn contributed to the accident.

Failure to take adequate safety measures

41     The Plaintiff next argued that the 1st Defendant had failed to take such measures as were necessary to ensure safety in respect of machinery, equipment, plant, article or processes used by employees at the Worksite, with specific focus being on the excavator.

42     Specifically, the Plaintiff contended that after the accident, the 1st Defendant adopted additional safety measures – in the form of: (a) requiring the excavator operator to horn once before moving off, and (b) having cameras installed on the side of the excavator which could be viewed from within the cabin to allow the operator a better view of the blind spots (the “Additional Measures”). All these, according to the Plaintiff, suggested that more could and should have been done to ensure the safety of the Plaintiff at the Worksite at the material time. That they were not done previously pointed to a want of care on 1st Defendant’s part.

43     I did not accept the Plaintiff’s argument. I did not find that the Plaintiff had discharged his burden of showing that the safety measures put in place by the 1st Defendant in relation to the operation of the excavator were inadequate.

44     First, based on the testimonies of the Plaintiff, a banksman system involving the blowing of a whistle and the use of designated hand gestures to signal for the excavator to move forward and/or to stop were in place at the material time:

NE 25 July 2022 p. 48-49 (Cross-examination of Plaintiff)

Q    Thank you Sir. Sir, perhaps, let me just focus on your job as a banksman in the present case here. I want to understand, and for the Court to understand, how do you go about directing the excavator operator. For example, were you given or were you taught to use a whistle to blow, let’s say, one time for the excavator to move forward or to use certain hand signals to ask the operator to start or stop the excavator? Is there such a system in place, could you explain to the Court?

A      We have a whistle, and we have hand gloves. To stop we will use this gesture. To resume work we will blow the whistle.

…..

Q    You also mentioned that you were given a whistle.

A     I would blow the whistle and then show …. my hand as stop.

Q     How about basically for the excavator to move forward, what would be the signal that you would show? So you would blow the whistle and ask the excavator to come towards you, is that correct?

A     Yes, Sir.

(emphasis added)

45     Secondly, based on the video clip adduced as part of Exh MV-1 of Murugaiyan’s affidavit[note: 1] (the “Video Clip”), it was also clear that before the excavator moved, it emitted loud beeping sounds which would have alerted persons in the vicinity that the excavator was about to move.

46     Thirdly, Safe Work Procedures and the Risk Assessments (“Safety Protocols”) were also put in place by the 2nd Defendant, which the 1st Defendant was required to comply with. The Safety Protocols included a safe system of work whereby the Operator should move the excavator only upon the directions of the banksman. Paragraph 4.2.6 of the Safety Work Procedure of the 2nd Defendant provided, in relation to the “Operation of Excavator”, as follows:

·    One banksman at least is required per team to be present during movement of machinery.

….

·    In the absence of banksman, the REO [(i.e. Registered Excavator Operator)] [is] not allowed to operate the excavator.

·    No one shall walk or work behind the excavator within the blind spot.[note: 2]

47     In addition, in the Risk Assessment of the 2nd Defendant, under the Work Activity of “Working near excavator” and the hazard of “workers injured by moving parts of excavator causing crushed in between/ property damaged/ fatality”, the “additional controls” stipulated that “excavator operator to check and ensure clear to move only to be given instruction by banksman”[note: 3].

48     Fourthly, the 1st Defendant’s employees involved in the excavation works were also briefed at daily toolbox meetings conducted by 2nd Defendant. During these toolbox meetings, they were briefed to look out for blind spots[note: 4].

49     Having regard to the safety measures put in place by the 1st Defendant, I found that the Plaintiff had not shown that the 1st Defendant was negligent in failing to take such measures as are necessary to ensure that adequate safety measures were taken in respect of any machinery, equipment, plant, article or process used by employees at the Worksite in breach of Section 12(3)(b)(i) of the WSHA. In the overall analysis, it was the negligence of the Operator in failing to wait for the signal of the banksman, and to check the blind spots prior to moving – i.e. the failure to comply with safety measures that were already in place – that ultimately led to the accident.

50     The fact that the two Additional Measures mentioned in [42] above were put in place post the accident did not without more suggest that the existing safety measures were inadequate. I agree with 1st and 2nd Defendants’ Counsel that the sufficiency of the safety measures should be assessed based upon the state of affairs at the time of the accident, and should not be judged with the benefit of hindsight: see BNJ (suing by her lawful father and litigation representative, B) v SMRT Trains Ltd and others [2014] 2 SLR 7 (at [92]).

51     In summary, I found that the 1st Defendant was negligent as employer in failing to provide effective supervision of its employees, but not in failing to take such measures as are necessary to ensure the safety of its machinery, plant and equipment.

Liability of 1st Defendant for negligence of the Operator

52     Alternatively, I found the 1st Defendant vicariously liable for the negligence of the Operator. It is trite law that employers can be found liable for the tortious acts of their employees if such acts were committed in the course of employment.

The Operator owed the Plaintiff a duty of care

53     Applying the Spandeck principles, given that the Plaintiff was the designated banksman for the excavator operated by the Operator, it was clearly foreseeable that any negligence on the part of the Operator might cause injuries to the Plaintiff. The requirements of physical and circumstantial proximity were also clearly fulfilled. A prima facie duty of care was thus owed. There were further no public policy reasons to negate the existence of such a duty of care.

The Operator was negligent in the management of the excavator

54     Having found that the Operator owed the Plaintiff a duty of care, I found that the Operator had breached its duty of care and was negligent in the operation of the Excavator in the following ways.

55     First, the Operator was negligent when he moved the excavator forward in the absence of a signal from the designated banksman, i.e. the Plaintiff, in breach of the Safety Protocols put in place by the 2nd Defendant. As noted in [46]-[47] above, under the Safe Work Procedures and Risk Assessment of the 2nd Defendant, the safe system of work envisaged by the 2nd Defendant required the Operator to move the excavator only in the presence, and upon the directions, of a designated banksman. In this regard, the reference to “banksman” in the Safe Work Procedures and Risk Assessment necessarily referred to the banksman of 1st or 2nd Defendant, and not a third party’s banksman. That the Operator knew that he was required to wait for 1st Defendant’s banksman’s (i.e. the Plaintiff’s) directions was further evident from paragraph 7 of his AEIC where he stated that “he wanted to wait for the Plaintiff to come to direct me to move the excavator”[note: 5].

56     The Operator, however, conceded that he ultimately moved the excavator on the instructions of the 3rd Defendant’s “banksman” because if he did not move, the traffic “will only [worsen]”[note: 6]. Indeed, the 1st Defendant’s Director, Arockiadoss, acknowledged during cross-examination that the banksman that the Operator should have taken instruction from should be a banksman from the 1st or 2nd Defendant, and not the 3rd Defendant. The Operator was thus negligent in moving the excavator upon the instructions of the 3rd Defendant’s banksman[note: 7].

57     Secondly, the Operator was also negligent in failing to make sure that the path of the excavator was clear before moving the excavator, in particular, in failing to check the excavator’s blind spots. Even if the Operator was of the view that it was necessary for him to move the excavator in the absence of directions from the designated banksman, he should have taken the additional precautions by making proper checks to ensure that the path of the excavator was clear. Instead, he compounded his errors in judgment by failing to make the proper checks.

58     The Operator’s testimony was that the Plaintiff was standing next to the arm of the excavator, and this was in the blind spot of the excavator[note: 8]. Thus, when the 3rd Defendant’s banksman told the Operator to move the excavator forward, he looked in front and saw no one in front of him. Based on paragraph 4.2.5 of the Safe Work Procedures, the Operator was required to “check blind spots before swinging arm or relocating the excavator”[note: 9]. When questioned by Plaintiff’s Counsel whether he had checked his blind spot, the Operator replied that he had checked but that he could “only see to a certain extent”. He added that “an operator in the seated position, even after checking, would not be able to see the … blind spot on the right”[note: 10].

59     I did not accept that there was no way for the Operator to have seen the blind spot on the right side where the Plaintiff was standing while the Operator was in the cabin. Even if he could not do so while seated, he could, and should, have moved his body, or looked out or stepped out of the cabin so that he could check the blind spots[note: 11]. In failing to do so, the Operator had breached his duty of care owed to the Plaintiff.

60     Having found the Operator negligent in the management of the excavator, it followed that 1st Defendant was vicariously liable for the Operator’s negligence as it was not disputed that the Operator was the 1st Defendant’s direct employee and that the accident happened in the course of his employment. The two-stage test for establishing vicarious liability as set out in Ng Huat Seng v Munib Mohammad Madni [2017] 2 SLR 1074 was clearly satisfied.

Liability of the 2nd Defendant as Main Contractor or Occupier

The 2nd Defendant owed Plaintiff a duty of care

61     Turning now to the issue of liability of the 2nd Defendant as the main contractor cum occupier of the Worksite. Following the decision of See Toh Siew Kee v Ho Lam Ferrocement Pte Ltd [2013] 3 SLR 284 (“See Toh Siew Kee”), the 2nd Defendant’s liability as occupier (and for that matter, as main contractor) would now be analyzed under Spandeck principles. In the context of negligence, the Spandeck test was the sole ultimate set of principles upon which a duty to take reasonable care under the law of negligence rested (See Toh Siew Kee at [52]-[54]).

62     In See Toh Siew Kee, VK Rajah JA observed that under the first limb of Spandeck, the vast majority of occupiers having control of the property which they occupy and/or the activities carried out there de jure owes a prima facie duty of care to lawful entrants. The threshold factual test of reasonable foreseeability was readily met in the case of occupiers as it was eminently foreseeable that entrants would suffer damage if occupiers did not take reasonable care to eliminate the danger. There was further undoubtedly physical proximity between an occupier and a lawful entrant merely by virtue of the fact that the entrant was physically situated on the occupier’s property. With regards lawful entrants, circumstantial proximity was tautologically present in the occupier-lawful entrant relationship because the hallmark of a lawful entrant’s presence on an occupier’s premises was consent to his presence on the part of the occupier. The prima facie duty of care essentially turns on the degree of control the occupier had over the property concerned and the activities carried out there.

63     On the facts of our case, the 2nd Defendant clearly had the requisite degree of control over the Worksite and the activities. The 2nd Defendant had put in place the necessary safety protocols such as preparing the Safety Work Procedure, Risk Assessment and conducting daily Toolbox Meetings. The 2nd Defendant also had the discretion to make changes to the safety protocol after the accident occurred. The requirement of proximity between the 2nd Defendant and the Plaintiff was thus fulfilled.

64     With regards the second stage of the Spandeck test, there were further no public policy considerations that might militate against the imposition of such a duty against the 2nd Defendant. As causation of loss was not disputed, the 2nd Defendant’s liability in negligence hinged on whether the 2nd Defendant had breached the duty of care owed to the Plaintiff.

Breach of duty of care by the 2nd Defendant

65     The Plaintiff argued that as the main contractor and occupier of the Worksite, the 2nd Defendant breached in its duty of care in the following respects:

(a)     Failing to provide proper training and safety briefings for the Plaintiff;

(b)     Failing to exercise proper supervision; and

(c)     Failing to coordinate and make arrangements between the Worksite and the 3rd Defendant’s Worksite (see PCS at [72]).

Failing to provide proper training and safety briefings for the Plaintiff

66     Under this head, the Plaintiff contended that while the 2nd Defendant’s supervisor, Kasinathan, had testified that the Plaintiff had been briefed during the daily toolbox meetings not to stand in the blind spot of the excavator, there was no record in the toolbox meeting notes that the workers had been briefed on the location of the blind spots. Kasinathan’s explanation, however, was the workers were in fact briefed orally on the location of the blind spots - “we can’t record everything down. We briefed them instead”:

NE, 28 September 2022 p. 82-83 (Cross-examination of Kasinathan by PC)

Q    In the same way, there is nothing in your toolbox meeting notes which states where the blind spots of the excavator are, would you agree?

A    Yes.

Q    Therefore, my question to you is, how would the workers know where the excavator’s blind spot is?

A     Because we have already briefed everyone before.

Q    You have very specific details about not standing under the excavator arm, not standing at the rear, not standing in the blind spot, following the traffic controller. Why do you not include important details such as where the blind spot is and that the operator should only take instructions from the banksman?

A    It is because we conduct these briefings on a daily basis.

….

Q    Therefore, I put it to you that the workers were never briefed about where the blind spot is and that the operator should only take instructions from the banksman. This is a put question, I only require a “yes” or “no” answer.

A    No, the operator is aware that he should listen to the banksman.

Q    What about the blind spot?

A     They know where the blind spots are.

Q     How would they know?

A     We have already briefed them on where the blind spots are during the briefings.

Q     Yes. But the fact that this---these important points were not recorded, I would therefore put it to you that this was not actually covered. Do you agree or disagree?

A     No, we have already explained this before.

(emphasis added)

67     Despite Kasinathan’s explanation, the Plaintiff submitted that the Plaintiff had not been properly briefed or trained by the 2nd Defendant to know where the blind spots of the excavator were as there were no documents or persuasive evidence to show that he was indeed aware of the same. I did not accept the Plaintiff’s arguments. It was not severely disputed that 2nd Defendant had put in place the Safety Protocols and conducted daily toolbox meetings at which the Plaintiff was reminded not to stand at the rear, under the arm or in the blind spot of the excavator. Though the exact locations of the blind spot were not recorded in the toolbox meeting minutes, I accepted Kasinathan’s testimony that these were briefed orally[note: 12]. It did not, in my view, make sense to train workers to look out for blind spots, without at the same time mentioning where the blind spots were.

68     In any event, the Plaintiff conceded that he was aware that one of the blind spots of the excavator was beside the arm of the excavator:

NE 25 July 2022 p. 70-71 (Re-examination of Plaintiff by PC)

Q:

Now, witness, I am going back to the put question, “You did not follow the toolbox instructions not to stand at the blind spot of the excavator.” You said you agreed. I earlier asked you to explain. What I meant, and I should be clearer, Your Honour, is what do you understand by standing at the blind spot of the excavator?

A:

I attended the meeting. I am not sure if they mentioned about the blind spot, but I think blind spot is beside the arm.

Ct:

Sorry, what? The blind spot is beside the arm?

A:

The blind spot refers to beside the arm. If the arm is extended and I’m standing there it cannot be seen. Only when the arm is raised can the person be visible.

 

(emphasis added)



Failure to exercise proper supervision.

69     The basis of this argument is that the 2nd Defendant’s supervisor, Kasinathan, was not present at the Worksite at the time of the accident, having left to attend to another team under his charge.

70     I was, however, of the view that by virtue of the Sub-contract entered into between 1st Defendant and 2nd Defendant (the “Sub-contract”), the 2nd Defendant was entitled to rely on its sub-contractor, the 1st Defendant, to supervise the excavation works, including supervising the Operator and the banksman. Notably, Clause 1.1 of the Sub-contract provided that 1st Defendant shall “provide and furnish all necessary resources for the proper and complete performance and acceptance of the works in relation to: (a) construction of the pipe trench … and (b) construction of joint pit/bay with steel decking…”[note: 13].

71     Following from this, I accepted Kasinathan’s testimony that he could not reasonably be expected to be stationed at the Worksite at all times as he coordinated a few teams at different worksites. That was why the 2nd Defendant sub-contracted the excavation works to the 1st Defendant in the first place, and appointed the 1st Defendant’s Nathan Raja as supervisor for the excavation team at the Worksite. Kasinathan testified during cross examination:

NE 28 September 2022 p. 79-80 (Re-examination of Plaintiff by PC

Q:

Therefore, you would agree that as the only one authorised to enforce safety protocols, if you leave the worksite, there is no one left to ensure that the safety protocols are adhered to, correct?

A:

Your Honour, I’m not the only one authorised to ensure the safety protocols. R Ayyakkannu is authorised as well. Along with him, the team supervisor, Nathan Raja, is also there to ensure this. I cannot be stationed here full time because I have a few teams. That is why we had appointed Nathan Raja for this team.

 

…..

Q:

I asked specifically about this risk assessment and whether there was evidence that Nathan Raja was aware of all of these details.

A:

Nathan Raja is the sub-contractor. He is the head of the team that was at the site of the accident. Our job is just to tell him what needs to be done. My job is just to arrange because I have four to five teams below me.

 

(emphasis added)



72     Accordingly, the mere fact that the 2nd Defendant’s supervisor, Kasinathan, was not at the Worksite at the time of the accident did not without more point to a breach of duty on the 2nd Defendant’s part.

Failing to coordinate between the Worksite and the 3rd Defendant’s Worksite.

73     Next, the Plaintiff averred that the 2nd Defendant had failed, as the main contractor and occupier of the Worksite, to coordinate and make the necessary arrangements with the 3rd Defendant with respect to the movement of the 3rd Defendant’s Truck into the 3rd Defendant’s Worksite.

74     For the same reason, I was unable to accept that the 2nd Defendant must personally coordinate with the 3rd Defendant’s worksite. The 2nd Defendant’s Kasinathan testified that two days before the accident, he had informed the 3rd Defendant that they would be doing excavation works around the 3rd Defendant’s Worksite shortly. In my opinion, it was not negligent for Kasinathan to thereafter leave the coordination of the 1st Defendant’s worksite and 3rd Defendant’s Worksite to the 1st Defendant’s Nathan Raja. Kasinathan could not be expected to be at the Worksite the whole day to coordinate with the 3rd Defendant’s site-supervisor whenever the 3rd Defendant’s large vehicles had to enter or leave the 3rd Defendant’s worksite. It was sufficient that such a role was left to Nathan Raja. That was the whole rationale for subcontracting the works to the 1st Defendant, so as to allow Kasinathan to manage other projects concurrently.

2nd Defendant’s vicarious liability for the Operator’s negligence

75     The Plaintiff went on to argue that the 2nd Defendant should assume dual vicarious liability for the Operator’s negligence, following the decision of Munshi Mohammad Faiz v Interpro Construction Pte Ltd and others and another appeal [2021] 4 SLR 1371 (“Munshi”).

76     The test to be applied in determining whether the 2nd Defendant should be vicariously liable for the Operator’s negligence, as set out in Ng Huat Seng v Munib Mohammad Madni and anor [2017] 2 SLP 1074 and applied in Munshi, is as follows:

(a)     In the first stage, the nature of the relationship between the 2nd Defendant and the Operator is examined to determine whether it is similar or analogous, or admits of similar considerations, to a relationship of employment as would make it fair, just and reasonable to impose liability on the 2nd Defendant vicarious liability for the tort of the Operator;

(b)     In the second stage, the question is whether there was a sufficient connection between the relationship between the 2nd Defendant and the Operator on the one hand, and the commission of the tort on the other. The defendant had to in some way have created or significantly enhanced, by virtue of that relationship, the very risk of the tort being committed.

77     Applying the above test, I was of the view that the 2nd Defendant should not be held vicariously liable for the Operator’s negligence.

Whether the 2nd Defendant and the Operator’s relationship is similar or analogous to a relationship of employment

78     First, the relationship between 2nd Defendant and the Operator was not similar or analogous to that of employer and employee. The Operator is an employee of the 1st Defendant. The 2nd Defendant had subcontracted the excavation works to 1st Defendant. Under the Sub-contract, the 1st Defendant was expressly termed an independent contractor of the 2nd Defendant (see clause 1.1 and 8 of the Sub-Contract). The Operator was thus the employee of an independent sub-contractor of the 2nd Defendant. The relationship between the 2nd Defendant and the Operator could not be said to be analogous to an employer-employee relationship or admitted of similar considerations to a relationship of employment as would make it fair, just and reasonable to impose liability on the 2nd Defendant vicarious liability for the tort of the Operator.

79     Separately, based on the evidence, besides prescribing the Safety Protocols and conducting the daily toolbox meetings, the actual degree of control exercised by the 2nd Defendant over how the Operator did his work was also extremely limited. The Plaintiff had testified that only the 1st Defendant would tell him and the Operator what had to be done, and that he did not take any instructions directly from the 2nd Defendant[note: 14]. The Operator himself testified that he was supposed to, and only took instructions, from either the Plaintiff or the 1st Defendant’s Nathan Raja and nobody else[note: 15]. The director of the 1st Defendant, Arockidoss, also testified that 2nd Defendant would leave the 1st Defendant to carry out the works at the site, and that Nathan Raja was in charge of executing the work on behalf of the 1st Defendant[note: 16]. The 2nd Defendant would thus inform the 1st Defendant what to do, and Nathan Raja would thereafter carry out the work[note: 17].

80     Kasinathan, the 2nd Defendant’s site supervisor, testified to similar effect, namely that the site was under the 1st Defendant’s Nathan Raja’s charge. Amongst other things, Nathan Raja would tell the banksman and the Operator what to do, and what not to do[note: 18].

81     Thus, just as the main contractor in Munshi was held not to be liable for the tort of the excavator operator in that case, I was of the view that the 2nd Defendant should similarly not be liable in the present case due to the minimal control exercised by the 2nd Defendant over how the work was to be done by the 1st Defendant’s employees.

Whether there was a sufficient connection between the 2nd Defendant and the Operator.

82     Secondly, the relationship between the 2nd Defendant and the Operator also did not create or significantly enhance the risk of the tort being committed. While the 2nd Defendant had put in place the Safety Protocols, and conducted the daily toolbox meetings, the Plaintiff had not shown that these measures were inadequate. The accident was the result of the manner in which the work was carried out by the 1st Defendant’s employees, i.e. the Plaintiff and/or the Operator. The 2nd Defendant did not control how the work was carried out on a day-to-day basis by the 1st Defendant’s employees. As such, the 2nd Defendant as the main contractor/occupier could not be said to have created or significantly enhanced the risk of the accident.

83     In my view, the 2nd Defendant should not be foisted with any liability solely because it had put in place the Safety Protocols, when no deficiency in the Safety Protocols had been adequately proven by the Plaintiff.

84     For the above reasons, I was of the view that the 2nd Defendant ought not assume any liability for the accident.

Claim against the 3rd Defendant

85     The Plaintiff’s claim against the 3rd Defendant was that the 3rd Defendant was vicariously liable for the acts of its traffic controller cum banksman, Neelamegam. The Plaintiff’s case was that as a traffic controller, Neelamegam, owed a duty of care to the Plaintiff and had breached the duty of care by failing to take proper steps to ensure that it was safe before directing the excavator to move forward.

Factual Dispute

86     Before examining the issue of the 3rd Defendant’s liability, there was a factual dispute as to whether the 3rd Defendant’s banksman, Neelamegam, did in fact direct the excavator to move forward.

87     The Plaintiff had stated in his affidavit that he had heard the 3rd Defendant’s banksman, Neelamegam, asking the excavator to move. However, during cross-examination, the Plaintiff took the position that he did not personally hear Neelamegam directing the Operator to move. Rather, he claimed he was told while he was in hospital by an unnamed friend who visited him that it was the “PUB person[note: 19] who had asked the … excavation operator to move”[note: 20].

88     On this point, the Operator (i.e. 1st Defendant) was unequivocal and consistent that he had only moved at the directions of the 3rd Defendant’s banksman.

89     The 3rd Defendant’s position, on the other hand was that Neelamegam never gave any instructions to the Operator to move the excavator.

Finding of Fact

90     On a balance of probabilities, I found that the 3rd Defendant’s banksman, Neelamegam, did in fact instruct the Operator to move the excavator, and it was based upon Neelamegam’s instructions that the Operator proceeded to move the excavator forward, running over the Plaintiff’s foot in the process. I considered the following.

91     First, the Operator testified during cross examination that the 3rd Defendant’s “banksman” directed him to move the excavator forward. I found it likely that the 3rd Defendant’s “banksman” referred to by the Operator was Neelamegam, given the 3rd Defendant’s Murugaiyan’s testimony that Neelamegam was the 3rd Defendant’s traffic controller at the material time[note: 21]. As Neelamegam was not called as a witness at trial, the Operator’s testimony that it was the 3rd Defendant’s banksman who told him to move remained unchallenged.

92     Secondly, the hypothesis that the Operator had moved the excavator forward upon the instructions of Neelamegam was rendered more likely by the fact there was otherwise no reason for the Operator to move the excavator. The Operator testified that he had no work to undertake further to the front of the Worksite[note: 22]. This point was not challenged at trial. In this regard, I found it likely that Neelamegam had first asked the Plaintiff to move the water barriers inwards. When that still did not create sufficient berth for the 3rd Defendant’s Truck causing the truck to hit the water barriers, Neelamegam then shouted to the Operator to move the excavator forward.

93     Thirdly, the Plaintiff had also deposed in paragraph 8 of his affidavit that it was the 3rd Defendant’s banksman that ordered the Operator to move:

“8. It was at this time that the 3rd Defendant’s banksman asked the excavator operator to move forward and it suddenly moved forward. The excavator then knocked me down and ran over my right leg. It pinned me down under the metal wheel-track of the excavator and I screamed out in great pain.”[note: 23](emphasis added)

94     The Plaintiff, however, departed from this position at trial when he said that he did not personally hear the 3rd Defendant’s banksman ask the Operator to move, and that he heard this from his colleagues at the hospital. I found it more probable than not that the Plaintiff in fact heard Neelamegam’s orders to move and therefore stated as such in paragraph 8 of his affidavit. I am fortified in my belief by the following:

(a)     Paragraph 8 of the Plaintiff’s affidavit, literally and objectively construed, conveyed the clear impression that the Plaintiff personally heard the 3rd Defendant’s banksman asking the Operator to move. As worded, there was nothing in paragraph 8 to suggest that the Plaintiff received such information second-hand from a third party;

(b)     the Plaintiff’s testimony in court that he heard “from a colleague” that Neelamegam had asked the Operator to move was not believable[note: 24]. The “colleague” was never identified. The Plaintiff’s testimony was further that all of the 1st Defendant’s workers, except the Plaintiff and the Operator, had left the Worksite to assist in unloading goods from a truck[note: 25]. This begged the question of which other colleague could possibly have been around to witness the 3rd Defendant banksman shouting to the Operator to move the vehicle. I found it likely that the Plaintiff changed his testimony at trial when he realised that he could be found to be contributorily negligent if he had remained in the excavator’s blind spot despite having heard Neelamegam asking the Operator to move the excavator.

Whether Neelamegam was negligent so that the 3rd Defendant would be vicariously liable

95     Overall, I found that Neelamegam owed a duty of care to the Plaintiff given his physical and causal proximity with the Plaintiff. Given the ongoing lax workplace safety and health practices that has led to a significant number of workplace accidents locally, there were no policy reasons why the said duty of care should not be held to exist.

96     Having found that Neelamegam owed Plaintiff a duty of care, I found that Neelamegam breached the duty of care when he asked the Operator to move the excavator forward in the circumstances of the present case. Neelamegam must have seen the Plaintiff behind the water barriers as the 3rd Defendant’s Truck was approaching. Murugaiyan testified as to the relative positions of himself and Neelamegam when the 3rd Defendant’s Truck arrived, and when it attempted to reverse into the 3rd Defendant Worksite. He positioned Neelamegam at “A” before the accident.

97     This would have placed the Plaintiff in the direct line of sight of Neelamegam. Even if the 3rd Defendant’s Truck did come in between Neelamegam and the Plaintiff at some point when it was attempting to reverse, the position of the 3rd Defendant’s Truck was dynamic, and there were no reasons to conclude that Neelamegam’s sight of the Plaintiff was always blocked by the 3rd Defendant’s Truck. At any rate, Neelamegam would also have been negligent if he had asked the excavator to move forward without having clear sight of the immediate surroundings of the excavator.

98     In this regard, I accepted Plaintiff’s Counsel’s argument that Neelamegam should have kept a look out before giving particular instructions to the Operator to move the excavator – this would have required Neelamegam to actively assess the safety of the situation prior to giving such instructions. Without ensuring that there was sufficient berth between the excavator and the Plaintiff before asking the Operator to move the excavator, and/or without alerting the Operator that the Plaintiff was in the Operator’s blind spot, Neelamegam was negligent, and his negligence contributed in part to the accident. The 3rd Defendant was therefore vicariously liable in part for the Plaintiff’s injuries.

Apportionment of Liability

99     It is trite that in apportioning fault, the key factors to be considered are causative potency and relative blameworthiness of the parties: see The Law of Torts in Singapore at [08.101].

100    In the parties’ closing submissions, the Plaintiff submitted that the Plaintiff should not be found to be contributorily negligent in any way. Alternatively, the Plaintiff should bear at most 5% liability on account of his contributory negligence: see PCS at 167.

101    Counsel for the 1st Defendant, the 2nd Defendant and the 3rd Defendant, on the other hand, commonly submitted that the Plaintiff should bear at least 50% contributory negligence for his injuries.

102    Counsel for the 1st and 2nd Defendants submitted that Plaintiff should bear substantial liability for contributory negligence (50%) on account of the following acts of the Plaintiff[note: 26]:

(a)     Failing to follow the safety protocols implemented at the Worksite, in particular, not to stand at the blind-spot of the excavator.

(b)     Failing to pay attention and/or be aware of his surroundings.

(c)     Standing in the blind spot of the excavator, without warning the Operator of his presence, despite knowing where the blind spot was and that it was unsafe for him to do so.

(d)     Standing directly beside an excavator which still had its engine switched on.

(e)     Failing to move away when he knew of ought to have known that the excavator was going to move forward.

(f)     Undertaking work that he was not tasked to do on his own accord when the same should have left to the 3rd Defendant’s traffic controller.

103    The 3rd Defendant similarly submitted that Plaintiff should be contributorily negligent to the extent of 50% on account of the following acts of the Plaintiff:

(a)     Knowingly placing himself in a dangerous position where the Operator could not possibly see him.

(b)     Standing next to the excavator even though there was a possibility that the excavator may move forward given that the engine of the excavator was switched on at the material time.[note: 27]

Whether Plaintiff was Contributorily Negligent

104    It is trite law that a party is contributorily negligent if he ought to have foreseen that if he did not act as a reasonable person, he may hurt himself.

105    In Froom v Butcher [1975] 3 WLR 379, the English Court of Appeal held that “contributory negligence is a man’s carelessness in looking after his own safety. He is guilty of contributory negligence if he ought reasonably to have foreseen that, if he did not act as a reasonable prudent man, he might hurt himself” (emphasis added).

106    In Ng Swee Eng (administrator of the estate of Tan Chee Wee, deceased) v Ang Oh Chuan [2002]2 SLR(R) 321, the High Court set out the principles of contributory negligence as follows (at [60] to [61]):

… The existence of contributory negligence does not depend on any duty owed by the plaintiff to the defendant and all that is necessary to establish a plea of contributory negligence is for the defendant to prove that the plaintiff did not in his own interest take reasonable care of himself and contributed by this want of care to his own injury.

…

The standard of care depends on foreseeability … [S]o contributory negligence requires the foreseeability of harm to oneself. A person is guilty of contributory negligence if he ought reasonably to have foreseen that, if he did not act as a reasonably prudent person, he might hurt himself. A plaintiff must take into account the possibility of others being careless. As with negligence, the standard of care is objective in that the plaintiff is assumed to be of normal intelligence and skill in the circumstances. (emphasis added)

Plaintiff was contributorily negligent

107    In relation to the Plaintiff, I agree that the Plaintiff had been contributorily negligent for the following reasons.

108    First, I found that the Plaintiff was standing in the blind spot of the excavator just before the excavator started to move forward. The Plaintiff admitted during cross-examination that he did not follow the specific instruction given at the toolbox meeting not to stand in the blind spot of the excavator. He also conceded that as a banksman, he should have known better than to stand in the blind spot of the excavator.

NE 25 July 2022 p. 40 (Cross-examination of Plaintiff by 1&2DC)

Q:     I put it to you as a banksman you should know better than to stand in the blind spot of the excavator; agree or disagree?

A:     I agree.

Q:    Thank you. I put it to you, therefore, you didn’t follow the instructions even at the toolbox meeting which is specifically not to stand in the blind spot of the excavator; agree? Agree?

A:     I agree.

Q:    I put it to you, you did not follow the safe work procedure; agree?

A:     I disagree. I had followed.

Q:     I put it to you, you did not keep a proper lookout of your surroundings just prior to the accident.

A:     I agree.

(emphasis added)

109    Admittedly, the Plaintiff subsequently gave a contradictory answer while he was being cross-examined by counsel for the 3rd Defendant when he disagreed with counsel’s put question that he did not follow the instructions given at the toolbox meeting not to stand in the blind spot of the excavator[note: 28]. However, during re-examination, the Plaintiff was asked specifically where the blind spot of the excavator was. He responded that the blind spot was beside the arm of the excavator:

NE 25 July 2022 p. 70 (Re-examination of Plaintiff)

Q:

Now, witness, I am going back to the put question, “You did not follow the toolbox instructions not to stand at the blind spot of the excavator.” You said you agreed. I earlier asked you to explain …. what do you understand by standing at the blind spot of the excavator?

A:

I attended the meeting. I am not sure if they mentioned about the blind spot, but I think blind spot is beside the arm.

Ct:

Sorry, what? The blind spot is beside the arm?

A:

The blind spot refers to beside the arm. If the arm is extended and I’m standing there it cannot be seen. Only when the arm is raised can the person be visible.

 

(emphasis added)



110    In this regard, the Video Clip clearly showed the Plaintiff standing next to the arm of the excavator before it collided into him. I am satisfied, on a balance of probabilities, that the Plaintiff was indeed standing in the blind spot of the excavator at the moment the excavator started to move forward.

111    In so doing, the Plaintiff had failed to follow the Safety Protocols imposed at the Worksite which required workers not to stand at the blind spot of the excavator. Paragraph 4.2.6 of the Safety Work Procedure of the 2nd Defendant specifically provided as follows:

·    No one shall walk or work behind the excavator within the blind spot[note: 29]

112    As a banksman, remaining in the blind spot of the excavator was precisely a risk that the Plaintiff would be looking out for and ensuring that other workers did not do when carrying out their work. The Plaintiff thus agreed during cross-examination that this role as a banksman was “principally to direct the excavator and also to ensure that no workers are near the excavator, especially the blind spot of the excavator operator when the excavator is moving”[note: 30](emphasis added). The Plaintiff was clearly aware of the risk and danger but nonetheless chose to ignore the same, to his own peril.

113    Secondly, Plaintiff’s act of standing directly beside an excavator which still had its engines on was inherently dangerous and risky. It was entirely foreseeable that the excavator may suddenly move off without realising that the Plaintiff was in the blind spot. Indeed, the Plaintiff stated that he would usually be directing the excavator from a long distance, usually at least 15 metres from the excavator[note: 31]. The Plaintiff also agreed during cross-examination that he should not be standing near the excavator when the engine was not switched off and at a distance of less than 15 metres away.

NE 25 July 2022 p. 40, 57-58 (Cross-examination of Plaintiff by 1&2DC)

At pg. 40

Q:    Sir, would you agree with me that it would be, rather, for safety reasons you should not stand near the excavator so long as the engine is not switched off? When I say near, I would say less than 15 metres, would that be correct?

A:    Yes.

At p. 57-58

Q:    Thank you. Sir, I will put it to you that it was unsafe for you to stand less than 15 metres to the excavator in the present case here as the engine of the excavator was not switched off. Would you 1 agree or disagree with this?

A:     I agree.

(emphasis added)

114    Thirdly, the Plaintiff’s failure to move away when the excavator started moving showed his lack of attentiveness to his surroundings. Based on the Video Clip, I accepted that before the excavator moved, its arm was lifted first and this was followed by various loud beeping sounds. The Plaintiff claimed not to have heard any of these[note: 32] and did not take any evasive action as a result. Given the loudness of the sound generated, I found it implausible that the Plaintiff would not have heard all these sounds and attempted some evasive action unless he was inattentive to his surroundings. Even if he were fenced in between the water barriers and the excavator, he could have shouted to alert the Operator that he was in the Operator’s blind spot and asked the excavator not to move. Alternatively, he could have attempted to cross over the water barriers to where Murugaiyan was (as shown in the Video Clip) to get out of the path of the excavator. He did none of these. Even if it were contended that the water barriers were too high for him to attempt to leap across, the fact remained that he made no attempts to take any evasive actions whatsoever. The Video Clip showed him just standing still on the spot after the boom of the excavator was lifted and the beeping sounds came on. The fact that the Plaintiff took no evasive action whatsoever suggested his lack of attention to his surroundings and/or carelessness as to his own safety when he perceived, or ought to have perceived, the dangers that presented when the excavator was about to move. Indeed, the Plaintiff admitted to not keeping a proper look-out of his surroundings prior to the accident:

NE 25 July 2022 p. 40-41 (Cross-examination of Plaintiff by 1&2DC)

At page 40

Q:    I put it to you, you did not keep a proper lookout of your surroundings just prior to the accident.

A:     I agree.

…

At p. 57-58

Q:    Okay. I put it to you, you were inattentive when you stood next to the excavator as you were busy communicating with the people from PUB; agree or disagree?

A:    Disagree.

Q:    I put it to you if you had been alert and attentive you would know that the excavator was going to move, and you should have gotten out of the way. Do you agree? And the accident would not have happened, sorry. Do you agree?

A:     I agree.

(emphasis added)

115    Fourthly, I also found on a balance of probabilities that the Plaintiff did hear the 3rd Defendant’s Neelamegam asking the Operator to move as he had originally stated in paragraph 8 of his affidavit. This should have heightened the Plaintiff’s level of vigilance further as to the potential dangers of standing next to the excavator which still had its engines on, since there was a distinct possibility that the Operator might move the excavator under pressure from Neelamegam.

116    Notwithstanding the above, I found that the Plaintiff’s causative potency and relative blameworthiness with regards to the accident to have been lessened to some degree due to the following.

117    First, the more direct cause of the Plaintiff’s injury was not the Plaintiff’s act of standing in the blind spot, but of the Operator moving forward suddenly, in breach of the Safety Protocols which required the Operator to move only upon the direction of the designated banksman.

118    Secondly, while there were beeping sounds before the excavator moved, I accepted that the reaction time the Plaintiff had was fairly short. The Plaintiff’s reaction (or the lack thereof) must be assessed against the predicament he was suddenly faced with, for which he only had a short span of a few seconds to react and decide what to do. As the Court of Appeal noted in Parno v SC Marine Pte Ltd [1999] 3 SLR(R) 377 (“Parno”), the courts are generally reluctant to hold an employee to be at fault if his acts are taken in the heat of the moment. Courts are slow to scrutinise in minute detail the conduct of a conscientious employee as primary responsibility for ensuring safety lies with the employer. Broadly, employees are judged by less exacting standards than employers. Mere errors of judgement do not ordinarily count against a Plaintiff, for a person’s conduct in the face of sudden emergency cannot be judged from the standpoint of what would have been reasonable in light of hindsight (at [64]).

119    In the present case, the 3rd Defendant’s Truck evidently had difficulties reversing into the 3rd Defendant Worksite. I accepted that the 3rd Defendant’s Truck had hit the water barriers at the first try[note: 33]. According to the Operator, traffic was being held up. Nathan Raja was nowhere to be seen, leaving the Plaintiff and the Operator in a lurch to deal with the situation. The Video Clip showed that the Plaintiff was pulling the water barriers inwards when the excavator moved forward and ran over the Plaintiff’s foot. The Plaintiff’s act of moving the water barriers was occasioned out of a perceived necessity. However, in choosing to do so while in the blind spot of an excavator and whose engine was still on, the Plaintiff showed an serious want of care for his own safety, for which the Plaintiff had to bear some blame. His recovery should therefore be reduced on account of his contributory negligence.

Cases on contributory negligence

120    Turning to the cases on contributory negligence, I did not think the Plaintiff’s contributory negligence should be as high as in the cases of Raju Tahzuddin v Lim Choon Chong (trading as Calpat Consultant Services) and Others [2008] SGDC 30 (“Raju Tahzuddin”) and Zhang You Hua v China Construction (South Pacific) Development Co. Pte Ltd [2003] SGDC 7 (“Zhang You Hua”) cited by Defendants’ Counsel, where both plaintiffs were found to be contributorily negligent to the extent of 50%.

121    In Raju Tahzuddin, the plaintiff, a construction worker, claimed against his employer (the 1st and 2nd defendants) and a contractor at the construction site where the plaintiff was working at (the 3rddefendant). The plaintiff-worker fell while sitting on a jack tied to a lorry driven by the 3rd defendant’s driver at the construction site. The plaintiff-worker was found to be contributorily negligent to the extent of 50%. However, the worker’s causative potency and blameworthiness in Raju Tahzuddin was, in my view, high. There, the worker had on his own volition stood up and sat on the jack that was partially hanging out of the lorry. There was no finding by the court that he was asked to do so, or what his reason for doing so was. The worker was injured when the jack fell off the lorry.

122    In Zhang You Hua, the plaintiff was a construction worker employed by the defendants. On the day of the accident, he was instructed by the defendants’ supervisor to move a bundle of heavy metal pipes. No specific instructions were give on how the bundle of pipes was to be moved and there was no supervision either. The plaintiff-worker and his co-workers chose to use wooden poles as levers to move approximately 1,000 kilogrammes of metal pipes, though they were not specifically instructed to do so. The plaintiff sustained spinal injuries while carrying out the work. The court found the plaintiff to be 50% liable. The causative potency in Zhang You Hua was again high.

123    In contrast, in the present case, I found that the Plaintiff had attempted to move the water barriers inwards because of an urgency caused by the attempts by the 3rd Defendant’s lorry to reverse into the 3rd Defendant worksite. The situation in the present case was more akin to the case of Parno v SC Marine Pte Ltd’s [1999] 3 SLR(R) 377 (“Parno”), cited in both Miah Rasel (at [48]) and Chen Qiangshi v Hong Fei CDY Construction Pte Ltd [2014] SGHC 177 (“Chen Qiangshi”) (at [223]) referred to by the Plaintiff in its Bundle of Authorities.

124    In Parno, the Plaintiff was a rigger on board a barge and the defendant was the shipowner. The barge was involved in piling operations wherein a hammer would be used to drive the piles into the seabed. To start the hammer, it was necessary to activate a device called the “starter” which would hoist the hammer vertically upwards. The Plaintiff was assigned to monitor the status and condition of the hammer from the piling tower deck. At the material time, piling had stopped temporarily because a pin on the hammer had become loose. The plaintiff sough to rectify the situation by attempting to temporarily replace the loose pin with a small wire. Whilst trying to replace the loose pin, the plaintiff stepped away from the platform and moved towards the hammer. As he was doing so, the “starter” fell onto his buttocks injuring him seriously. The Court of Appeal found that the Plaintiff’s act of approaching the hammer at a time when the “starter” had yet to come down was not a deliberate act of folly; it was at most a momentary lapse on the Plaintiff’s part. While the plaintiff knew he should not have approached the hammer before the “starter” had come down, he had momentarily overlooked that safety aspect in his anxiety to replace the loose pins as he was concerned for the safety of the entire piling operations. The plaintiff did what he thought at that moment was best for the safety of the entire operations, and the situation involved an urgency. The Court of Appeal found the Plaintiff one-third liable for his own injuries.

125    In my view, the present case bore several similarities to Parno’s case. The Plaintiff’s act of removing the water barriers while standing next to the excavator, in its blind spot, was not a deliberate act of folly. The Plaintiff did so as he wanted to alleviate an urgent traffic condition at the Worksite, very much like the plaintiff in Parno’s case, who decided to replace the pin failing which a grave risk would have been caused to the piling operations.

126    Another relevant precedent in my view was Neo Siong Chew v Cheng Guan Seng [2013] SGHC 93 (“Neo Siong Chew”). In Neo Siong Chew, the plaintiff sustained injuries from an accident involving an excavator operated by the 1st defendant. The 2nd defendant was the main contractor who had appointed Hock Po Leng Landscape & Construction Pte Ltd to cut and uproot trees at the worksite. Hock Po Leng in turn subcontracted the job to the 3rd defendants. The Plaintiff was an independent contractor of the 3rd defendant. The 3rd defendants hired an excavator from Gim Soon Heng Engineering Contractor to undertake the job. Gim Soon Heng subcontracted the work to the 1st defendant, an independent excavator operator. The plaintiff was supervising and working with the 3rd defendants’ workers at the worksite when the excavator operated by the 1st defendants reversed into the plaintiff while the plaintiff was walking along the construction site’s cemented path towards a side gate and injured him. The High Court found the Plaintiff 30% contributorily negligent for his injuries for the following reasons:

(a)     The plaintiff had warned the 3rd defendants’ workers to keep away from the excavator, suggesting that he appreciated the danger posed by working in close proximity with the excavator.

(b)     The size of the excavator and the noise generated by it meant that the plaintiff must have noticed the excavator as he was making his way to the side gate and a reasonably prudent man in the plaintiff’s position would have kept a close eye on the excavator and given the excavator a wide berth. The plaintiff was therefore careless in failing to keep a safe distance and a proper lookout for the excavator.

127    Like the plaintiff in Neo Siong Chew’s case, the Plaintiff, as a banksman, was similarly aware of the dangers of standing near, and in the blind spot of, an excavator which had its engines on. Indeed, he conceded that as a banksman, his role was to ensure that other workers did not do the same: see [112] above[note: 34]. The Plaintiff was also aware of the difficulty the 3rd Defendant’s Truck had in reversing, and would have appreciated that there was a reasonable possibility that the excavator might move forward to create more berth for the 3rd Defendant’s Truck. Like the plaintiff in Neo Siong Chew’s case, the Plaintiff was therefore careless in failing to keep a safe distance from the excavator.

128    While certain factors in the present case would point to a higher level of contributory negligence than in Neo Siong Chew’s case (e.g. Plaintiff being in the blind spot where he knew he should not have been, and his failure to keep a proper look out and to take evasive action), there were other factors that pointed to a lower level of contributory negligence in the present case (e.g. the Plaintiff here was conscientiously attempting to resolve an urgent situation that had sprung up, and had little reaction time when the excavator started to move). Considered in totality, the extent of the plaintiffs’ blameworthiness in both cases appeared comparable.

129    I will also deal with the case of Munshi which was heavily relied upon by the Plaintiff in support of his contention that the Plaintiff should not be held contributorily negligent at all.

130    In Munshi, the plaintiff-worker was also injured by an excavator. The 2nd defendant was the main contractor of a project. The 2nd defendant had employed the 1st defendant as a subcontractor to the project and the plaintiff was an employee of the 1st defendant. The 2nd defendant had engaged the 3rd defendant to supply an excavator and a trained and qualified excavator operator.

131    On the day of the accident, the foreman first instructed the plaintiff to direct the excavator operator to stop the excavator. The foreman then went into the excavated pit to inspect it. After noting that there were still some remnants of earth that had to be removed using a spade, the foreman instructed the plaintiff to fetch a spade from a toolbox near the entrance of the Project’s worksite. While fetching the spade, the plaintiff walked near the excavator, at which point the excavator (operated by the excavator operator) moved and collided into him. The plaintiff was pinned under the metal wheel-track of the excavator and suffered various personal injuries including a spinal fracture.

132    The High Court in Munshi held that the plaintiff was not contributorily negligent for the accident. In reaching this conclusion, the Court took into account the fact that the excavator operator had already been directed to stop the excavator. As such, it was reasonable for the plaintiff to expect that the excavator would remain stationary and that the foreman would not direct the excavator operator to move the excavator for no good reason.

133    I, however, found Munshi’s case to be distinguishable in several key respects:

(a)     Unlike the worker in Munshi’s case, the Plaintiff here had stood in the blind spot of the excavator in breach of the Safety Protocols, and with full knowledge that it was unsafe to do so. As a banksman, this was the type of risk that the Plaintiff should have been fully apprised of and have taken steps to guard against.

(b)     The court in Munshi found it was reasonable for the plaintiff to expect that the supervisor there would not direct the excavator to move at the relevant time. In contrast, on our facts, the Plaintiff would have seen the 3rd Defendant’s Truck arrive and encountering difficulties reversing into the 3rd Defendant’s Worksite. It was precisely because of this that the Plaintiff had attempted to move the water barriers inwards. It was therefore reasonably foreseeable to the Plaintiff, and reasonable for the Plaintiff to expect, that the excavator may subsequently have to move forward to allow even more space for the 3rd Defendant’s Truck to reverse.

(c)     I have also made the finding of fact that the 3rd Defendant’s Neelamegam did in fact shout to the Operator asking the Operator to move forward. If the Operator who was seated inside the cabin of the excavator had heard this, it was more probable than not that the Plaintiff who was standing outside would have heard Neelamegam’s directions as well. It would therefore have been within the reasonable contemplation of the Plaintiff that there was a high possibility that the excavator might have to move to make way for the 3rd Defendant’s Truck. The Plaintiff therefore ought to have taken the necessary steps to protect himself, e.g. by alerting the Operator of his presence, or by being more alert and ready to take evasive action should the contingency materialize. In this regard, the Plaintiff had admitted during cross examination that if he had been alert and attentive, he would have known that the excavator was going to move and he should have gotten out of the way:

NE 25 July 2022 p. 41 (Cross-examination of Plaintiff by 1&2DC)

Q:    I put it to you if you had been alert and attentive you would know that the excavator was going to move, and you should have gotten out of the way. Do you agree? And the accident would not have happened, sorry. Do you agree?

A:     I agree.

(emphasis added)

The 1t Defendant’s Liability

134    In relation to the 1st Defendant’s actions, I found that it was the Operator’s (1st Defendant’s employee’s) act of moving the excavator forward without being given the go-ahead by the banksman that was most causatively linked to the accident.

135    The 1st Defendant’s relative blameworthiness was also high:

(a)     the Operator breached the Safety Protocols by moving without instructions from his banksman. He chose to take instructions from the 3rd Defendant’s banksman, which the Operator acknowledged was in breach of the Safety Protocols.

(b)     The Operator also failed to check his blind spot before moving off – see [57] to [59] above. During cross-examination, it appeared that all the Operator checked were the mirrors, which would not have revealed any persons who may be standing in the excavator’s blind spot[note: 35]. The checks made by the Operator were evidently insufficient.

(c)     The 1st Defendant’s blameworthiness was also compounded by the fact that the 1st Defendant did not have a supervisor on site at the material time to direct the movement of the excavator and the shifting of the water barriers at a time when the 3rd Defendant’s truck was attempting to reverse. The 1st Defendant attempted to minimise the Operator’s fault by asserting that the Operator was “under substantial pressure from the 3rd Defendant banksman as well as the commotion and had to make a judgment call”. However, the reason the Operator was in this predicament was precisely due to Nathan Raja’s absence from the Worksite, which resulted in no one coordinating the movement of the excavator and persons in the vicinity of the Worksite. This led to Plaintiff and Operator being left to their own devices, and taking steps as they thought appropriate without any coordination.
