The 1st Defendant, as noted above, thus failed in ensuring that there was effective supervision of the workers at the Worksite at the material time.

The 3rd Defendant’s liability

136    As for the 3rd Defendant’s causative potency and blameworthiness, I had earlier found that the 3rd Defendant’s banksman, Neelamegam, did ask the excavator to move forward. In asking the Operator to move without ensuring that excavator’s path was clear, and/or without alerting Operator that the Plaintiff was standing next to the excavator, Neelamegam fell below the standard of care required of him. Neelamegam, and hence the 3rd Defendant (by reason of vicarious liability), should bear some liability.

137    The causative potency and blameworthiness of Neelamegam was, however, low for the following reasons:

(a)     While the 3rd Defendant asked the Operator to move, the 3rd Defendant did not have full knowledge of the 1st Defendant’s operational protocols. Neelamegam could very well have assumed that the Operator would move in a manner that took into account the safety of the workers in the vicinity;

(b)     By the Operator’s testimony, he did not move immediately upon hearing Neelamegam shouting for him to move. He waited some 3-5 minutes for the Plaintiff banksman to give him the signal to move, which never came. Again this weakens the causative potency between the Neelamegam’s acts and the accident.

Final Apportionment of liability

138    It is trite that apportionment is more an exercise in discretion rather than clinical science. The court exercises a general discretion, taking into account the causative potency as well as the blameworthiness to be assigned to the different parties involved: see Chen Qiangshi’s case at [216].

139    Having regard to the causative potency and relative blameworthiness of Plaintiff, the 1st Defendant and the 3rd Defendants, I was of the view that the level of the Plaintiff’s contributory negligence in the present case should be in the region of that ascribed in Parno and Neo Siong Chew’s case. I therefore found the Plaintiff to be contributorily negligent and liable for his own injuries to the extent of 33.33%.

140    It followed that the 1st Defendant and the 3rd Defendant should collectively bear 66.67% liability for the Plaintiff’s injuries.

141    As between the 1st Defendant and the 3rd Defendant, having regard to the causative potency and relative blameworthiness of the parties discussed above, I was of the view that the 1st Defendant should be the bulk bearer in terms of liability. The accident primarily arose because of the negligence of the Operator. The 3rd Defendant’s blameworthiness and causative potency was in comparison low. The attribution of 10% liability to 3rd Defendant would be fair and reasonable in the circumstances. The 1st Defendant should bear the remaining two-thirds of the liability not assumed by 3rd Defendant, i.e. 56.67%.

142    I therefore apportion liability as follows:

Plaintiff:

33.33%

1st Defendant:

56.67%

2nd Defendant:

0%

3rd Defendant:

10%



Judgment

143    Based on the foregoing, I made the following orders:

(a)     There will be Interlocutory Judgment for the Plaintiff against the 1st Defendant and the 3rd Defendant jointly and severally for 66.67% of damages to be assessed.

(b)     In light of the offer-to-settle served by the 1st to 3rd Defendants (the “OTS”), the 1st Defendant and the 3rd Defendant shall pay the Plaintiff’s costs (up to the interlocutory judgment stage) on a standard basis up the date of the OTS (i.e. 28 July 2022), and the Plaintiff shall pay the 1st Defendant and the 3rd Defendant’s costs (up to the interlocutory judgment stage) on an indemnity basis from 29 July 2022 to the date of the interlocutory judgment (i.e. 19 January 2023).  

(c)     The Plaintiff’s claim against the 2nd Defendant is dismissed with costs.

(d)     The Plaintiff shall pay the 2nd Defendant’s costs (up to the interlocutory judgment stage) on a standard basis up the date of the OTS (28 July 2022), and on an indemnity basis from 29 July 2022 to the date of the interlocutory judgment (i.e. 19 January 2023).

(e)     As no contribution proceedings have been brought on record by the 1st and 3rd Defendant against each other, I make no contribution orders as between the 1st and 3rd Defendants under sections 15 and 16 of the Civil Law Act 1909.
